issues.title: 花了两天，终于搞定了腾讯视频，不仅不会慢，也解决了之前只能下载分段的问题，还可以用-p "mpv merge-files"播放视频,1080P也没有VIP限制，解决了关于腾讯视频的大部分issue

issues.title: [youku]update api
issues.body:
NOTE:

1.  ```yxon``` not impled. F. I. 10 segs in hd3, 8 ones in hd2, 5 ones both in mp4 and flv. 28 extra network requests will be sent, which makes the program seem stuck or produces lots of noise in the debugging log. #1058

2.  Failed with ```http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMjc3MjQ0MjEwMA==.html```. ep40 of Zetianji. But it works when downloading ep1 and ep45. Perhaps you should curse the CDN before a VIP user of youku find out what's wrong.

---

1. ```yxon```没有放进代码里。比如一个视频，hd3有10个片段，hd2有8个，mp4和flv各5个，那么一共需要发出28个网络请求，程序会看上去像卡住了一样，或者输出大量没什么用的debugging log。另外可以参考 #1058 ，有人需要。

2. 择天记第40集下载会失败（hd3，其他分辨率正常）。但是择天记的第一集或是第45集都正常，选1080p需要vip所以也没法在浏览器里面看是不是正常。大概只能怪youku的CDN了。

need to bring back the handling of password-protected videos, then it'll be perfect :shipit:
Ok,I'll re-try it.But for the Second,I think we can try direct connect to obtain the url.if fail,then use 'Unblock youku''s proxy.

For the 2nd point: it's not important now. As quite a lot of users complain about incomplete videos, we can stick with `k.youku.com`as long as it fixes the issue. For simplicity, whether to use Unblock Youku's proxy (or another proxy) should be left to users to choose, we really shouldn't bother with that in `extractors/youku.py`.

@DagonDD  

Some issue here, when using --playlist, Correct file names on the playlist is created but  sometime the same file is being downloaded over and over again with a different name. This is a very destructive bug.

I debug it, and found the reason: in https://github.com/soimort/you-get/blob/develop/src/you_get/extractors/bilibili.py#L215-L218

when using `--playlist` argument, here will append the first `playinfo` to all of other page which overwrite the result from `bilibili_api` later.

so, just comment the lines(two parts):
```
        if playinfo is not None:
            playinfos.append(playinfo)
        if playinfo_ is not None:
            playinfos.append(playinfo_)
```
I test download a video list, but hadn't do more test.

pls try, and let me known whether it works, if work fine, I'll create a new pr later.

Hard to tell just yet, sense it happens once in a while at a random time.
Need to do more tests on more playlists.

Thank you so much for looking into this.

issues.title: Extremely slow download (~50KB/s) from YouTube
issues.body:
Seemingly this is due to a new restriction imposed by YouTube. See https://github.com/ytdl-org/youtube-dl/issues/30102
The tool `yt-dlp` has a workaround for this.

Hello @rosynirvana,
Thanks for the Pull Request. We :heart: our contributors!
Please wait for one of our human maintainers to review your patches. This may take a few days to weeks. Also, please understand that although your Pull Request may or may not be eventually merged, we value all contributions equally.

有个遗留问题，bangumi_title ep_no ep_title应该用什么样的各式
上一个commit是``` '{0} [{1}]'.format(bangumi_title, ep_title)```
现在是``` '{0} [{1} {2}]'.format(bangumi_title, ep_no, ep_title)```

Thank you so much for your PR.

Can you do me a favour by making a force push on your branch to clean up the commit log? 

Also, I am wondering whether we still need the retry function. What if we remove this? This would make the behaviour of the code more predictable, I boldly suppose?
Perhaps we should keep the timeout parameter for it can help to bypass some IP limitations.

I agree. 

I am noticing this issue even with normal users with Android or HTML5 player. I would say do not push ourselves too hard and see how it goes.

Again, thanks for your PR. It would be great if the commit log is cleaned. Open a new PR if you want, and let's get it merged.

cleaned up

After some tests now I believe ```timeout``` param should be removed. Socket blocking for one second is quite normal in the real world. Timeout after only one second sounds somewhat insane. ```urlopen_with_retry``` can also catch ```socket.timeout``` exception so this can mess up the control flow.

In this patch it is kept with ```timeout``` set to 15 for there could be a chance someone really need it. If anyone would like to bypass IP limitations with short timeout, please change it to a rather short time period(F. I. 1 in the old commit).

---

测试之后我发现```timeout```确实应该被移除，socket timeout指的应该是socket block的时间，实际上socket block 1秒，没数据可以读写，是非常正常的事情（比如线路繁忙，比如无线网稍微波动了一下），所以1秒就超时可能有点过了。另外```urlopen_with_retry```也会捕获```socket.timeout```这个异常，所以流程控制会变得混乱。

但在这个patch里，```timeout```还是有的，但是默认值是15. 如果有人需要用这个超时来完成一些事情，比如觉得这个patch还不如原来的好用，把```timeout```的值改短就行了，例如改成原来的1。

对于某些HTTPError 403 503的情况，如#1913 #1938 （在后半，没有开新issue）
考虑两点：

1. ```url_info``` 太多次访问使CDN暂时block了client
2. CDN自身的错误

在这个commit中，parse api返回的xml，获取文件格式和所有分片的大小，不再使用```url_info```。
使用```url_info```来测试返回CDN的可用性。

**但是有些时候还会出现所有CDN都不可用的情况。**
403不是本项目的问题。
先提供一个workaround

issues.title: Fixed bilibili download 403 error
issues.body: It's not just the UA's fault, because other browsers can access it successfully with the same UA. Add a Accept request-header and everything seems to work.

今天，更新到最新版之后还是403 error，看了一下代码
`headers = {'Accept': '*/*', 'Accept-Language': 'en-US,en;q=0.5', 'User-Agent': ua}`
改为
`headers = {'Accept': 'text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,image/webp,image/apng,*/*;q=0.8,application/signed-exchange;v=b3', 'Accept-Language': 'en-US,en;q=0.5', 'User-Agent': ua}`
就可以正常用了

可能对Accept的内容做了反爬吧，加上浏览器的Accept头之后就可以了

你可以试试改一下bilibili.py 50行处的headers的代码
        headers = {'Accept': 'text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,image/webp,image/apng,*/*;q=0.8,application/signed-exchange;v=b3', 
        'Accept-Language': 'en-US,en;q=0.5', 
        'User-Agent': ua , 
        'Cookie': "填自己的cookie", 
        'DNT': 1, 
        'Upgrade-Insecure-Requests': 1, 
        'Sec-Fetch-User': '?1', 
        'Sec-Fetch-Site': 'same-site', 
        'Sec-Fetch-Mode': 'navigate', 
        'Referer': 'https://search.bilibili.com/'

昨天晚上同样遇到了 403 错误的问题
只需要在 bilibili.py 的 headers = {'Accept': '*/*', 'Accept-Language': 'en-US,en;q=0.5', 'User-Agent': ua} 上添加 cookie 请求头即可

cookie 需要是自己的bilibili的请求cookie!

issues.title: Add huaban.com support.
issues.body: Sample link: http://huaban.com/boards/24803867/ --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/soimort/you-get/976)

comments_data.body:
Firstly, thanks for the pull request.

A rough review:

Your implementation of `huaban_download_board()` perfectly ignored the current structure of `you-get` - it has its own version of progress bar, own file handling, own `stdout` printing/logging, and even own `KeyboardInterrupt` exception catching (why?).

The code is not wrong - but as it differs quite a lot from `you-get`'s coding style, it will make itself extremely hard to maintain. If we improve any high-level routine in `common,py`, the code here will not benefit from our changes much, or even risk to break (e.g. it relies on some low-level API like `url_save`, which is not supposed to be used by extractors directly).

Especially, if you want to propose an enhancement to the current progress bar, or anything else that could be shared among all extractors, please consider doing a patch on `common.py`, instead of putting them all together specific to one site, isolated.

There are two reasons make me feel hard to fit the download process of `Huaban` into the workflow provided by `common.py`.

First, there maybe multiple types of images in one "board". `download_urls` accepts only one extension name for a whole stream, and also `print_info`.

The second one is new images will be added into a "board". I want to continuously download images from a "board", but the default naming scheme is based on current number of files to be downloaded.

The reasons above explained why I have my own versions of file handling and logging.

For the progress bar, I wish its animation is based on the count of pieces of files rather than the size, because it isn't worth to make hundreds of connections to check the images' size of a "board". `SimpleProgressBar`'s animation is based on size and `PiecesProgressBar` just count down the number.

Lastly, it seems I misunderstood the exception handling strategy in [youku.py](https://github.com/soimort/you-get/blob/develop/src/you_get/extractors/youku.py#L121), it raise the `KeyboardInterrupt` but I bypass it. :disappointed: 

@soimort

> For the progress bar, I wish its animation is based on the count of pieces of files rather than the size, 
> because it isn't worth to make hundreds of connections to check the images' size of a "board".

That is a very good point, and that's why I prefer you to make those changes in `common.py`, rather than do it in your own `huaban.py`.

`download_urls` does support only one extension, and you're also right, that the default naming scheme is based on the number of pieces (starting from 0). I haven't tested your PR on a real machine yet, but I guess you could just call `download_urls` as many times as want; doing that won't look very nice, though.

Or, if you can abstract some of these functionalities as common routines, put them into a common place (`common.py`) so later implemented extractors can benefit from them.

> Lastly, it seems I misunderstood the exception handling strategy in youku.py

Oh, forgot to say, but the `KeyboardInterrupt` in `youku.py` is used to skip a certain video when downloading a playlist (so if you have a video you don't like, `Ctrl-C` will let you skip it, instead of terminating the whole downloading process)

> you could just call download_urls as many times as want

Yes, that will makes things more simple and I no longer need to care about the progress bar, but as you said, it is not so good looking.

This is the output of my customized version file handling code:

```
you-get http://huaban.com/boards/24803867/
Site:       花瓣 (Huaban)
Title:      爱上咖啡的味道

Downloading 105 images in 爱上咖啡的味道 ...
     %[====------------------------------------] 8/105
```

and this is the output of "calling `download_urls` for one image at a time":

```
 you-get http://huaban.com/boards/24803867/
Downloading 爱上咖啡的味道 (603832678).jpeg ...
 0.0% (  0.0/  infMB) ├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤[1/1]  208 kB/s

Downloading 爱上咖啡的味道 (579557455).jpeg ...
 0.0% (  0.1/  infMB) ├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤[1/1]  557 kB/s

Downloading 爱上咖啡的味道 (579557420).jpeg ...
 0.0% (  0.1/  infMB) ├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤[1/1]  514 kB/s
```

Do you really prefer this way? If so, I push the new commit.

Actually I prefer the progress bar (probably other things also) to be fixed in `common.py`. For now, removing `EnhancedPiecesProgressBar`and simply making use of `download_urls()` will do the job.

I don't have time to refactor this part of `common.py`, so let's keep things simple that if I want to rewrite the whole codebase someway, simpler extractors would be easier to improve, i.e., the shorter, the better.

(Tip: it's completely up to you whether you would intend to change that, since you can always keep it as your own fork of `you-get`.)

Making hundreds of HEAD requests to check for all pieces' sizes, as you said, is inefficient for image downloading. The cause is, `you-get` was designed to be a video downloader (normally there won't be too many pieces for a video), so handling images wasn't my concern at the very beginning. Certainly, we have extended its scope to image downloading now.
Yes, you are right, keeping simple is the best choice.
Looks good. Could you please rebase this branch?

I know this is a stupid question, but, how could I do that?

I read the README of this project and done the following steps before making the last commit:

```
git remote add upstream https://github.com/soimort/you-get.git
git fetch upstream
git rebase upstream/develop
```

I have a few experiments of opening PRs for other projects. After my code being merged, I would use the commands above to update my forked repo from the upstream, but I never do a rebase before the merging, so I'm not sure what that means : \

Normally `rebase` is used _before_ merging, since it _rewrites all your commits you made ahead of the base branch_, in this case, `soimort/develop`.

I can still merge your commits without rebasing; but it'd be better to make sure we have a tidy "linear" history, and that your PR will end up with a nicer look (purple "Merged" sign instead of a red "Closed" sign)

Please post your `git branch -va` before I can tell what the problem is.

Here are the outputs:

```
git branch -va
* develop                   2a1a541 [Huaban] Refactoring.
  remotes/origin/0.4        fb8acf4 version 0.4.111
  remotes/origin/HEAD       -> origin/develop
  remotes/origin/develop    2a1a541 [Huaban] Refactoring.
  remotes/origin/gh-pages   741a354 version 0.4.324
  remotes/origin/master     bf9910a version 0.4.324
  remotes/upstream/0.4      fb8acf4 version 0.4.111
  remotes/upstream/develop  2a80fb5 Merge branch 'zhangn1985-for-up' into develop (fix #906)
  remotes/upstream/gh-pages 2062c68 version 0.4.330
  remotes/upstream/master   bf495b1 version 0.4.330
```

This one is out-of-date with the base branch: (on the upstream)

```
  remotes/upstream/develop  2a80fb5 Merge branch 'zhangn1985-for-up' into develop (fix #906)
```

Unfortunately commit https://github.com/soimort/you-get/commit/b35a0bd9f92a6298f58bb5281ba2bfd541d04e1e (which has been pushed to upstream after your last commit) changed `src/you_get/extractors/__init__.py`, so you might have some conflicts to resolve. It's very easy, though.

```

(it's ok to force push to a temporarily branch, but you might want to use something other than `develop` next time)

Since there's no more conflict, it should not stand out-of-date anymore. If that reason is true, then whenever someone pushes some new commits to the upstream, every existing unmerged Pull Request should've been rendered outdated. That's obviously not the case. I don't know what GitHub's mechanism is; maybe they just don't bother rechecking a PR again even if it's updated.

The problem seems to be that the program failed to properly utilize the temporary `.download` file after interruption (by connection error, user intervention, whatsoever). If you observed carefully: you shall notice that the total size (to finish after interruption) equals to the downloaded size (before interruption) + expected size.
[*] Do note that the program attempts to retry upon interruptions (errors).

~~To workaround this problem~~: > Quote "[/README.md](https://github.com/soimort/you-get/blob/84a5611939443dbf03e9751a0b33598934647652/README.md#pause-and-resume-a-download)" § [Pause and resume a download](https://github.com/soimort/you-get#pause-and-resume-a-download): > > To enforce re-downloading, use the `--force`/`-f` option. (**Warning:** doing so will overwrite any existing file or temporary file with the same name!) It failed... Didn't overwrite the temp file but instead started the writing on top of it. And eventually ended up with AssertionError... (size mismatch)

Probably fixed: > Quote [cww0614](https://github.com/soimort/you-get/pull/2804#issue-417659586): > > When `url_save` is passed a list of urls (`is_chunked = True`), and the download is aborted, then the next time that you-get resumes the download, it will append the video data from beginning to the `.download` file, because it does not send a correct `Range` header when resuming. > > Several "exceeding 100%" issues might be related to this: #2703, #2768 > > Steps to reproduce: > > ... > > Basically, the idea of this pull request is to maintain the starting and ending offset for each chunk. And when resuming, it skips downloaded chunks by comparing the file size and ending offsets, and computes the correct `Range` for the first unfinished chunk.

issues.body: Come from https://github.com/soimort/you-get/pull/463 fix #390 [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/soimort/you-get/783)

comments_data.body:
The implementation looks good.

The copyright restricted videos (which used to be only accessible via the m3u8 method before), as discussed in [you-get#463](https://github.com/soimort/you-get/pull/463#issuecomment-68547897) and [youtube-dl#6377](https://github.com/rg3/youtube-dl/issues/6377), seem no longer to be an issue now. Here are some links to test: (previously not available)
- http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMTQ3MDcyNTYw.html
- http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XNTc2NDk2MDMy

So, nice job.

However, the code is a bit tangled: `import urllib.parse` is not needed, and stuff for debugging purpose like `pdb` should be removed as you commit. The most important thing you forgot is, the code for processing passwords was commented out and never put back, so it will not work for password protected videos. (Test link: http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMzg1ODY1MTIw.html, password: `123`).

I'll do the clean-up later, so no further action is needed on your side.

Thanks.But it supports password protected videos.The code is at the handle part of `"error_code"`.That also should add "Referer" http header to http request.To fix #793.Maybe need some modifications on `common.py`.

`Referer: http://static.youku.com` worked fine for me just hours ago -- Now I'm getting 403 errors everywhere, as someone already mentioned in #793.

```
urllib.error.HTTPError: HTTP Error 403: Forbidden
```

<del>Could this 403 be related to cookies?</del> I suppose having only the referer is not enough.

Update: Seems like a **YES**. After setting the handler for cookies I haven't met a single 403 error!

Requesting the `play.youku.com` doesn't need cookies.But in original way,need to request `pl.youku.com`,And that needs cookies.

~~There are't `HTTP Error 403` in my tests yet.  ~~
~~What's the url you are testing?~~

The `HTTP Error 403` comes out when requesting `k.youku.com`.

I can confirm that `k.youku.com` also requires cookies. And you will eventually get blocked.

![screenshot from 2015-12-09 08-25-11](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/342945/11679200/11f556b4-9e4f-11e5-9f28-c7fefabc7171.png)

You can open the `k.youku.com` url in browser.
There are two ways to fix it.Depends on the `yxon=1` parameter in the end of `k.youku.com` url.
1.Now the `k.youku.com` url doesn't have `yxon=1` parameter,We can add http headers or cookies for downloading.But the `-p` argument in `you-get` may be corrupted.
2.if we add `yxon=1` to the `k.youku.com`.The url will be `k.youku.com/......&yxon=1`.And it will give back a string which contain a url of video.You can test it in browser.And that url doesn't  need special  http headers or cookies. 
**3.Of course,you also can obtain the final video address from the answer headers of `HEAD` request to `k.youku.com`.**

> You can open the k.youku.com url in browser.

No, you can't, unless your browser already has its cookies (which is often the case if you have visited the Youku page in your browser before).

You should try with your browser's incognito mode, and see if things still work out fine even without any cookies.
Yes,the `k.youku.com` also requires cookies.Use browser's incognito mode,it indeed give back `403 Error` to me.

however, still prefer my own [modified version](https://github.com/mo-han/mo-han-toolbox/blob/master/mylib/bilibili.py), which gets rid of the following issues:
- streams sorted by size rather than resolution, while sometimes bilibili produces videos with size of 720p bigger than 1080p (it may be bilibili's fault but i have to change the code)
- sometimes the condition line `if current_quality is None or qn < current_quality:` cause 1080p60 1080p+ streams lost, i don't know why but after bypassing this if code, issue gone

@mo-han 
Hello, have you  fixed the issue that bilibili api do not return the [1080P+ 高码率] option? I notice that this particularly  happened to some old videos that initially only support 1080P and Bilibili add the 1080P+ option later. The modified one from you can detect [dash-hdflv2 高清 1080P+] with -i but still unable to download. 
Also notice that: the 1080P+ with newest videos have H265 encoding, while the old videos that added 1080P+ later have the H264 encoding. The link you mentioned above is invalid and I cannot access it.

update: Fixed by manually add dash_streams in def extract. Thank you very much~

@NoNova7 
the link is out-dated because i changed repo files' names occasionally
the repo path is `mo-han/mo-han-toolbox`
the bilibili lib file path is `mylib/site_bilibili.py`
for now won't edit that link url in last comment because maybe someday it will be invalid again

i simply replaced a "if" line from `if current_quality is None or qn < current_quality:` to `if True:`
which makes VIP quality streams always detectable (didn't notice any fail until now)
since it's detected then it's able to download, unless the target stream is not selected by default
by default you-get choose the "best" stream, which is stream with largest size actually
however sometimes the highest level "quality" stream is not the biggest sized one
i personally met few videos with 720p as the biggest size stream (1080p{60,+} is smaller)
in such cases, you-get sort streams by size from large to small, resulting into lower quality stream sorted on top and downloaded by default
i changed its sort method from "size first" to "quality/resolution/stream_id first"
i hadn't come across aforesaid issues since then (but i'm not 100% sure if this is your case)

you-get choose HEVC stream over AVC ones
i like this feature and didn't touch its code (never dig into that)

there's another bilibili downloader (not developed by me) which is promising:
http://github.com/lifegpc/bili
its author has done great job on parsing almost all kinds of resouces on bilibili site, and succeeds to provide all kinds of downloading features
i don't use it because i don't need it yet

hope this helps

issues.title: youku: warn about segments skipped due to paywall
issues.body: This is especially helpful in cases where the entire video is blocked by paywall, resulting in an unhelpful error message ``` you-get: [Failed] Cannot extract video source. ``` I spent quite a few minutes debugging a URL like that,^ which could have been saved by the message ``` you-get: Skipping 27 out of 27 segments due to paywall ``` added by this commit. ^The video is completely region-blocked where I am, so I didn't know it was behind a paywall before feeding it to you-get — with a Mainland-based extractor proxy of course. That should explain my initial confusion — it would have been obvious if I checked its availability in a Unblock Youku-enabled browser session first. Still, more self-contained information should make you-get better. --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/soimort/you-get/1744)

comments_data.body:
Hello @zmwangx,
Thanks for the Pull Request. We :heart: our contributors!
Please wait for one of our human maintainers to review your patches. This may take a few days to weeks. Also, please understand that although your Pull Request may or may not be eventually merged, we value all contributions equally.

祝您健康!

![](http://thecatapi.com/api/images/get?format=src&type=gif)
IMO the original url should be printed. Number of segments skipped does not help the user.
Not sure what you mean. This is just a warning, essentially telling the user "look, there are this many segments we can't do anything about". All intermediate URLs are useless without keys.

Original urls are those urls from input of users.
Users should not be informed with segments.

1. It's rather pointless to echo user input. Echoing back the URL is at best slightly more clear when users are downloading multiple videos, but even then due to the sequential nature of you-get, it's extremely easy to know exactly which URL the warning applies to.

    Note that currently error messages don't contain original URLs either. Not following conventions makes the (frankly already quite inconsistent, due to its nature) project inconsistent.

2. > Users should not be informed with segments.

    Users are already exposed to the total number of segments (that are not skipped) and the segment currently being downloaded in the progress bar. So this assertion has no ground.

    > Number of segments skipped does not help the user.

    As a user myself, it totally helps. When a video claimed to be 1GB (in fact, that number isn't available across the board, or it could be a wrong number) ended up with only 3 segments totally 100MB, knowing that 27 segments were skipped due to paywall instantly makes the situation clear, and helps estimate how much I'm missing out.
You mean the patch does not try to inform users which url has not been downloaded completely, but to tell users what percent of a single video file is downloaded?

> You mean the patch does not try to inform users which url has not been downloaded completely

Again, this is obvious from context.
Any sample URLs for testing?

Sure, plenty of examples can be found on vip.youku.com. Just find a VIP-only episode of a TV show, e.g.,

```
$ you-get --debug https://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMjY0Mzk0Mzk2MA==.html

you-get: Skipping 24 out of 24 segments due to paywall
site:                优酷 (Youku)
title:               热血长安 第一季 24 千年太岁
stream:
    - format:        hd3
      container:     flv
      video-profile: 1080P
      size:          1209.7 MiB (1268423229 bytes)
    # download-with: you-get --format=hd3 [URL]

audio-languages:
    - lang:          国语
      download-url:  http://v.youku.com/v_show/id_XMjY0Mzk0Mzk2MA==

you-get: [Failed] Cannot extract video source.

I'm not able to maintain site support like this, because they are... too many. And because most of them are rather easy to implement, I'm afraid that merging all things like this will make our repo too bloated.

Notice that [the universal extractor](https://github.com/soimort/you-get/pull/712) was able to handle a few similar sites (xvideos, xhamster, ...), so if there's a more universal way to do this, I'm happy to hear about it.
